This was my first time making pecan rolls. I did it for food day in our office. Everyone said they were really good. They were not buttery enough for my taste but that could be easily solved. I had no problem adding more flour to the dough to be able to knead it. I added probably a cup more for it to stop being sticky. Then they rose beautifully I used 1 pkg of a quick rise - Red Star and another package of active yeast - Flieshmans. It was one of my better bread rises by mixing the different yeasts. Also helped that I let the bread rise in closet that had floor vent so it was warm. Definatly make it again and maybe do a variation like add slices of ham and cheese for an appetizer in lieu of a sweet treat. Best of luck to all!

Rating: 4
After reading the previous reviews I did the following: I used milk instead of water, and butter instead of oil. I did not use eggs. I used rapid rise yeast by mixing the yeast into the dry ingredients, heating up the milk and butter to 120o and then mixing the wet ingredients into the dry ingredients. I kneaded the dough for exactly 10 minutes being careful to minimize flour additions. Let the dough rest for 10 minutes, and then roll out and cut into rolls and place in pan to rise for one hour. The rolls were excellent! Using rapid rise yeast cuts down the time to make these in half. I phoned the Fleishman Yeast customer care representitive (1-800 number on the back of the package) due to my first batch not rising. These were the instructions she gave me. The rolls were not too sweet, were light and fluffy, and were gobbled up by my husband and my three year old by the end of the day.

